Hit this problem when trying to get `tap` to work in "--compat" mode.

This snippet shows how `tap` runs a single file with tests:
```js
        debug('js file', file)
        /* istanbul ignore next - version specific behavior */
        const experimental = /^v10\./.test(process.version) && /\.mjs$/.test(file)
          ? ['--experimental-modules'] : []

        const args = [
          ...options['node-arg'],
          ...experimental,
          file,
          ...options['test-arg']
        ]
        tap.spawn(node, args, opt, file)
```

`node` is defined as:
```js
const node = process.execPath
```

Later it constructs a command to be run using something like this:
```js
const cp = require("child_process");
const p = {
  spawn: async (name, ...rest) => cp.spawn(...rest);
};
await p.spawn(this.name, this.command, this.args, options);
```

`tap` is not aware that it must run the process by using `deno run --compat --unstable` args and only uses `deno`.

### Why

Some native libraries return function pointers to expose further API. Such as GLFW exposes a `glfwGetProcAddress` function which is used to get pointer to the OpenGL API function. I'm currently using a helper library written in C to call function pointers in [my project that uses GLFW](https://github.com/DjDeveloperr/deno_gl). I'm sure there are much more use-cases than just this, like calling temporary callbacks returned from native land.

### Suggestion

Introduce a new API to wrap a function pointer + a function definition into a JS function, such as:

```ts
// on `DynamicLibrary`
fnptr<Fn extends Deno.ForeignFunction>(ptr: Deno.UnsafePointer, def: Fn): StaticForeignFunction<Fn>;
```

(I'm not sure about name of the method)

which can be used something like this:

```ts
const fn = lib.fnptr(ptr, {
  parameters: [...],
  result: "...",
});

fn(...);
```

