I propose adding a new API `Deno.ThreadSafeCallback` to create C-style callbacks which can be passed down to FFI.

### Why

Currently, #13162 adds support for passing JS callbacks wrapped in a C function to FFI. However, that will not work for callbacks that will be moved to another thread as V8 Isolate cannot be accessed from other threads. Instead, we could implement a new mechanism for creating C callbacks which do not use any V8 API, as a result which can be called from any thread but handled again on Isolate thread. It is also much easier & safer to implement than trying to do same with JS callbacks using V8 API.

### Proposal

```ts
declare class ThreadSafeCallback<Fn extends Deno.ForeignFunction> {
  readonly pointer: Deno.UnsafePointer;
  
  // It will create a new callback resource that is basically just a Rust channel
  // and a closure. The closure will create a new Rust channel that will wait for return
  // value and sends the arguments & new channel's sender end to the previous
  // Rust channel. Further logic is handled by `next`.
  constructor(def: Fn);

  // This will spawn a tokio blocking task to wait for the function to be called
  // on other thread (as such isolate thread is not blocked). Basically, it will poll
  // for new messages in the Rust channel.
  async next(): Promise<ThreadSafeCallbackContext<Fn>>;

  // This is just to unref any current or future async op call made by
  // `next` function because it would by default cause Deno event loop
  // to not exit until the function has not been called.
  unref(): void;

  // Since it is a resource, we'll explicitly manage it's lifetime.
  close(): void;

  // For allowing `for await of` loops to handle function calls (basically wraps the `next` function)
  *[Symbol.asyncIterator](): AsyncIterableIterator<ThreadSafeCallbackContext<Fn>>;
}

declare class ThreadSafeCallbackContext<Fn extends Deno.ForeignFunction> {
  readonly arguments: MapFunctionToArguments<Fn>;

  // This will send return value to the another Rust channel created
  // when the callback was called, causing the wait for it to end.
  return(value: MapNativeTypeToJS<Fn["result"]>): void;
}
```

### Example usage

```ts
// Creating:
const callback = new Deno.ThreadSafeCallback({
  parameters: ["i32", "i32"],
  result: "i32",
});

// Pass callback.pointer to FFI

// Handling:
callback.next().then((ctx) => {
  ctx.return(ctx.arguments[0] + ctx.arguments[1]);
});
// or like this:
for await (const ctx of callback) {
  ctx.return(ctx.arguments[0] + ctx.arguments[1]);
}
```

### But but...

This approach has a problem. The created callback function cannot be called from main thread (or thread same as the Isolate), otherwise it deadlocks waiting for return value on same thread. One solution is to have an hybrid approach which calls either directly V8 function or falls back to this when called from other thread.

