I'm in need of two utilities:

1. to return whether a given port is available
2. to returns an open port

Open source implementations of a `isAvailablePort` and `getAvailablePort` look similar to the following:

```ts
function isAvailablePort(port: number): boolean {
  try {
    const listener = Deno.listen({
      transport: "tcp",
      hostname: "127.0.0.1",
      port,
    });
    listener.close();
    return true;
  } catch (_e) {
    return false;
  }
}


const MIN_PORT = 49152;
const MAX_PORT = 65534;
export function getAvailablePort(): number {
  let randomPort: number;
  do {
    randomPort = Math.floor(Math.random() * (MIN_PORT - MAX_PORT + 1) + MIN_PORT);
  } while (!isAvailablePort(randomPort));
  return randomPort;
}
```

Both of these approaches are less than ideal. `isAvailablePort` try/catches on an attempted `Deno.listen`... not sure why the port's state wouldn't be accessible without such a measure. Meanwhile `getAvailablePort` uses `Math.random` and a while loop; this code brushes off the (albeit very low) likelihood of repeat numbers and all ports within the range being occupied. While this may work, it's not exactly *clean code*.

Is there a better way to implement these utilities?

I'm experimenting with interfacing with web streams to read data from a Redis server over `Deno.Reader`. I've found that web streams can be up to 90% slower, which surprised me. I initially assumed web streams would be far faster.

I'm aware that streams aren't yet optimised. However, @littledivy told me that streams should at least be at the same level as `Deno.Reader`/`Deno.Writer` in terms of performance. I'm opening this issue to study what performance improvements can be made around this and similar use cases.

Note: one must [install Redis](https://redis.io/docs/getting-started/installation/) for the snippet to work.

```ts
import { writeAll } from "https://deno.land/std@0.159.0/streams/conversion.ts";
import { BufReader } from "https://deno.land/std@0.159.0/io/buffer.ts";
import { TextLineStream } from "https://deno.land/std@0.159.0/streams/mod.ts";

await Deno.spawn("redis-server", { args: ["--daemonize", "yes"] });

const port = 6379;
const encoder = new TextEncoder();
const decoder = new TextDecoder();

/** Deno.Reader */
const redisConn1 = await Deno.connect({ port });
const bufReader = new BufReader(redisConn1);

Deno.bench({
  name: "buffer",
  group: "read",
  async fn() {
    await writeAll(redisConn1, encoder.encode("PING\r\n"));
    const { line } = (await bufReader.readLine())!;
    decoder.decode(line!);
  },
});

/** Web streams */
const redisConn2 = await Deno.connect({ port });
const streamReader = redisConn2.readable
  .pipeThrough(new TextDecoderStream())
  .pipeThrough(new TextLineStream())
  .getReader();

Deno.bench({
  name: "web streams",
  group: "read",
  async fn() {
    await writeAll(redisConn2, encoder.encode("PING\r\n"));
    await streamReader.read();
  },
});

addEventListener("unload", async () => {
  await writeAll(redisConn1, encoder.encode("SHUTDOWN\r\n"));
  redisConn1.close();
  redisConn2.close();
});
```

