I maintain a system that uses Deno to load and execute modules in a semi-trusted environment. I recently upgraded it to v1.26, and was quite surprised to learn that the new [Cache API](https://deno.com/blog/v1.26#cache-web-api) allows data sharing between these modules, despite being given very limited permissions (and no file write permissions at all).

I think I have narrowed it down to the fact that we load modules dynamically from the same entry point, and the cache is shared based on the location of the entry point. A simple reproducer:

```
// run.ts
const mod = await import(Deno.args[0]);
console.log(await mod.fn());

// write.ts
export async function fn() {
  const c = await caches.open("v1");
  await c.put(new Request("https://www.example.com/leak"), new Response("sensitive data"));
  return "cached";
}

// read.ts
export async function fn() {
  const c = await caches.open("v1");
  const rsp = await c.match(new Request("https://www.example.com/leak"));
  return await rsp?.text();
}

// $ deno run --allow-read=write.ts run.ts ./write.ts
// $ deno run --allow-read=read.ts run.ts ./read.ts
```

Is this expected behavior? Is there a way to isolate the process's caches?

I tried overriding `DENO_DIR`, but that didn't do it, and I don't see any other documented flags that would seem to be relevant.

