I think the latest incarnation of the subprocess API is confusing because it tries to combine both configuration and state into a single struct. This means that `Deno.Command` can represent both a "to-be-spawned" and an "already-spawned" subprocess.

This is very difficult for users to understand, and for us to explain: #16719

I don't think there is any value in this, other than reducing the number of globals by one.

I propose we split configuration and subprocess state into two interfaces: `Deno.Command` for the "to-be-spawned" configuration, and `Deno.Child` (or `Deno.ChildProcess`) for the "already-spawned" subprocess.

You would use the API as follows:

```ts
// run to completion
const cmd = new Deno.Command("cat", { args: ["./foo.txt"] });
const output = await cmd.output();

// run to completion synchronously
const cmd = new Deno.Command("cat", { args: ["./foo.txt"] });
const output = cmd.outputSync();

// spawn and manage manually
const cmd = new Deno.Command("cat", { args: ["./foo.txt"] });
const child = cmd.spawn();
const stream = child.stdout.pipeTo(Deno.stdout.writable);
const [_, status] = await Promise.all([stream, child.status]);
assert(status.success);
```

The type definitions:

```ts
/** **UNSTABLE**: New API, yet to be vetted.
 *
 * The interface representing the return values of a terminated subprocess.
 *
 * @category Sub Process
 */
export interface ChildStatus {
  /** If the child process exits with a 0 status code, `success` will be set
   * to `true`, otherwise `false`. */
  success: boolean;
  /** The exit code of the child process. */
  code: number;
  /** The signal that caused the subprocess to terminate, if the subprocess was
   * terminated by a signal. */
  signal: Signal | null;
}

/** **UNSTABLE**: New API, yet to be vetted.
 *
 * The interface returned from calling {@linkcode Deno.Command.output} or
 * {@linkcode Deno.Command.outputSync} which represents the result of spawning
 * the child process, waiting for it to finish, and collecting the output.
 *
 * @category Sub Process
 */
export interface SpawnOutput extends ChildStatus {
  /** The buffered output from the child processes `stdout`. */
  readonly stdout: Uint8Array;
  /** The buffered output from the child processes `stderr`. */
  readonly stderr: Uint8Array;
}

/** **UNSTABLE**: New API, yet to be vetted.
 *
 * Options which can be set when creating a {@linkcode Deno.Command}.
 *
 * @category Sub Process
 */
export interface CommandOptions {
  /** Arguments to pass to the process. */
  args?: string[];
  /**
   * The working directory of the process.
   *
   * If not specified, the `cwd` of the parent process is used.
   */
  cwd?: string | URL;
  /**
   * Clear environmental variables from parent process.
   *
   * Doesn't guarantee that only `env` variables are present, as the OS may
   * set environmental variables for processes.
   */
  clearEnv?: boolean;
  /** Environmental variables to pass to the subprocess. */
  env?: Record<string, string>;
  /**
   * Sets the child process’s user ID. This translates to a setuid call in the
   * child process. Failure in the set uid call will cause the spawn to fail.
   */
  uid?: number;
  /** Similar to `uid`, but sets the group ID of the child process. */
  gid?: number;

  /**
   * An {@linkcode AbortSignal} that on abort will kill the subprocess by
   * sending the process a SIGTERM signal.
   *
   * Due to the synchronous nature of the {@linkcode Command.outputSync} API,
   * the abort signal can not be triggered to kill synchronously executing
   * subprocesses.
   */
  signal?: AbortSignal;

  /** How `stdin` of the spawned process should be handled.
   *
   * Defaults to `"null"`. */
  stdin?: "piped" | "inherit" | "null";
  /** How `stdout` of the spawned process should be handled.
   *
   * Defaults to `"piped"`. */
  stdout?: "piped" | "inherit" | "null";
  /** How `stderr` of the spawned process should be handled.
   *
   * Defaults to "piped". */
  stderr?: "piped" | "inherit" | "null";

  /** Skips quoting and escaping of the arguments on Windows. This option
   * is ignored on non-windows platforms. Defaults to `false`. */
  windowsRawArguments?: boolean;
}

export class Command {
  constructor(command: string | URL, options?: CommandOptions);

  /**
   * Spawn a subprocess with the configured options, and wait for it to finish,
   * collecting it's output once it is done.
   *
   * Will throw an error if `stdin: "piped"` is set.
   *
   * If options `stdout` or `stderr` are not set to `"piped"`, accessing the
   * corresponding field on {@linkcode Deno.SpawnOutput} will throw a `TypeError`.
   */
  output(): Promise<SpawnOutput>;

  /**
   * Spawn a subprocess with the configured options, and synchronously wait for
   * it to finish, collecting it's output once it is done.
   *
   * Will throw an error if `stdin: "piped"` is set.
   *
   * If options `stdout` or `stderr` are not set to `"piped"`, accessing the
   * corresponding field on {@linkcode Deno.SpawnOutput} will throw a `TypeError`.
   */
  outputSync(): SpawnOutput;

  /**
   * Spawns a subprocess with the configured options, and returns a
   * {@linkcode Deno.Child} instance that can be used to interact with the
   * subprocess.
   */
  spawn(): Deno.Child;
}

/** **UNSTABLE**: New API, yet to be vetted.
 *
 * The interface for interacting with a child process. This is returned from
 * {@linkcode Deno.Command.spawn}.
 *
 * @category Sub Process
 */
export class Child {
  get stdin(): WritableStream<Uint8Array>;
  get stdout(): ReadableStream<Uint8Array>;
  get stderr(): ReadableStream<Uint8Array>;
  readonly pid: number;
  /** Get the status of the child. */
  readonly status: Promise<ChildStatus>;

  /** Waits for the child to exit completely, returning all its output and
   * status. */
  output(): Promise<SpawnOutput>;
  /** Kills the process with given {@linkcode Deno.Signal}. Defaults to
   * `"SIGTERM"`. */
  kill(signo?: Signal): void;

  /** Ensure that the status of the child process prevents the Deno process
   * from exiting. */
  ref(): void;
  /** Ensure that the status of the child process does not block the Deno
   * process from exiting. */
  unref(): void;
}
```

