When defining custom inspect functions using the `Deno.customInspect` symbol or `Symbol.for("Deno.customInspect")`, two arguments are passed to the function:

- the Deno.inspect function
- the inspect options object, with the addition of `indentLevel`, and `depth` will never be undefined

This is currently not documented anywhere and there are no types for it.

Typing is also a bit of an issue here because the user has to manually assign the type somewhere, as shown in the example below:

```ts
declare global {
  namespace Deno {
    interface InspectOptions {
      indentLevel?: number;
    }

    interface CustomInspectOptions extends InspectOptions {
      depth: number;
      indentLevel: number;
    }

    type CustomInspect = (inspect: typeof Deno.inspect, options: CustomInspectOptions) => string;
  }
}

/* A - manually assigning types to the arguments */

export class A {
  constructor(public value: unknown) {}

  [Symbol.for("Deno.customInspect")](
    inspect: typeof Deno.inspect,
    options: Deno.CustomInspectOptions,
  ) {
    return `A(${inspect(this.value, options)})`;
  }
}

/* B - extending Object with a unique symbol key */

const customInspect = Symbol.for("Deno.customInspect"); // or use `Deno.customInspect` instead

declare global {
  interface Object {
    [customInspect]?: Deno.CustomInspect;
  }
}

export class B {
  constructor(public value: unknown) {}
}

// argument types are automatically infered
B.prototype[customInspect] = function (inspect, options) {
  return `B(${inspect(this.value, options)})`;
};
```

Use cases for this include:

- Creating better inspect output for wrapper types.
- Using the `indentLevel` allows for multiline output which fits nicely into the builtin inspect output.
- It generally allows for a better debugging experience for custom types.

