Benchmarking functions that mutate their operands is currently impossible to measure without also including the setup portion of the run in the measurement. This will cause the benchmarks to give erroneous results when measuring relative performance of such functions.

Consider the case where we have two functions performing a mutative operation on a large array that we would like to compare:

```ts
const a = <T>(arr: T[], ...items:T[]): T[] => { /* impl A */ };
const b = <T>(arr: T[], ...items:T[]): T[] => { /* impl B */ };

const getSample = () => {
  const sample: number[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < 1e6; i++) sample.push(i);
  return sample;
};

Deno.bench('a', {baseline: true}, () => {
  const data = getSample();
  a(data, -1);
});

Deno.bench('b', () => {
  const data = getSample();
  b(data, -1);
});
```

In this case, creating the data on each run will incur an almost fixed time cost on each run measurement.

I could not identify a way to run a function before or after each execution to set up the data outside of the measurement run.

One solution would be to allow specifying `setup()` and `teardown()` functions by extending the `BenchDefinition` interface:

```ts
type BenchDefinition = Parameters<typeof Deno.bench>[0]

type ExtendedBenchDefinition<T> = BenchDefinition & {
  setup: () => T;
  fn: (data?: T) => unknown;
  teardown: () => void
}
```

That way, one could provide provide pre- and post-run function outside of the measurement loop to setup up or reset the requisite data:

```ts
// using setup
Deno.bench({
  name: 'a',
  setup() { return getSample(); },
  fn(data) {
    a(data, -1);
  }
});

// or alternatively using teardown:
let data = getSample();
Deno.bench({
  name: 'a',
  fn() {
    a(data, -1);
  },
  teardown() {
    data = getSample();
  }
});
```

