In a company internal application I maintain users are allowed to provide their own plugins in TypeScript. The plugin code is loaded at runtime, after checking a mandatory signature of the plugin code it is imported using dynamic imports. Plugin developers are free to do what they need to do in their plugins as long as they implement the plugin interface and sign their code with a key that is on our allow-list.

When we tried to upgrade our environment to Deno v1.31.0 our unit tests started failing, specifically the tests verifying that our plugin import does not accept invalid code. Starting from this release invalid code was rejected in the first test that used the invalid code, but accepted in all tests after the first. The console output also did not show any sign of type checking happening for tests after the first whereas in previous versions this did appear in the output for all tests (see console output below).

Since the first test always succeeded, but subsequent tests (in the same `deno test` execution) failed, I assumed the error to be something cache-related and in fact I could get the other tests to reject the code if I changed the test code in irrelevant ways like adding a space or newline somewhere in the code.

Using `git bisect` in the deno repository I managed to locate first occurrence of the error in commit https://github.com/denoland/deno/commit/b3e88e0681248631b4bf8e4d9cd2e4d2c651f333 and thus PR https://github.com/denoland/deno/pull/17692

So this will probably require further testing in one of the updated crates. I'm not familiar enough with that code to say something definitive right now, though from what I've seen mentioned in PRs I think this may be related to the new additive graph.

