[`Deno.inspect`](https://deno.land/api@v1.32.1?s=Deno.inspect) can be used to serialize a value for display (e.g. in the console).

There is an option [`Deno.InspectOptions.showHidden`](https://deno.land/api@v1.32.1?s=Deno.InspectOptions#prop_showHidden) which is described by the documentation this way:

> Show an object's non-enumerable properties.

Given an object with non-enumerable properties, I expected that I could invoke the function like this:

```ts
Deno.inspect(obj, { showHidden: true })
```

and see the non-enumerable property entries serialized in the resulting string. However, that option seems to be ignored.

Here's an example for reproduction in Deno and Node.js, with outputs from `console.log`'s built-in serializer for comparison:

`inspect_hidden.mjs`:
```js
const inspectorMap = {
  deno: () => ({
    serializer: "Deno.inspect",
    inspectHidden: (value) =>
      Deno.inspect(value, { colors: true, showHidden: true }),
  }),
  node: async () => {
    const { inspect } = await import("node:util");
    return {
      serializer: "node:util.inspect",
      inspectHidden: (value) =>
        inspect(value, { colors: true, showHidden: true }),
    };
  },
  unknown: () => ({
    serializer: "String",
    inspectHidden: (value) => String(value),
  }),
};

const runtime = typeof globalThis?.Deno?.inspect === "function"
  ? "deno"
  : typeof globalThis?.process?.versions?.node === "string"
  ? "node"
  : "unknown";

const { serializer, inspectHidden } = await inspectorMap[runtime]();

for (
  const descriptor of [
    { value: "bar" },
    { enumerable: true, value: "bar" },
  ]
) {
  const obj = {};
  const prop = "foo";
  Object.defineProperty(obj, prop, descriptor);

  console.log();
  console.log(
    `${prop} is enumerable:`,
    Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(obj, prop).enumerable,
  );

  console.log("serializer:", "console.log");
  console.log(obj);

  console.log("serializer:", serializer);
  console.log(inspectHidden(obj));
}

```

